Local engagement as a countermeasure against populism
PARIS – The parties once dominant in Western democracies were shaken at their core.
Many – among others in France, Italy, Greece and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of U.S. President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of the once dominant parties swing between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to recognize a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their opponents' supporters as "pitiful," as Hillary Clinton did just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too terrified by the populist wave to launch a counteroffensive.
Yet neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with a diagnosis of the inadequacies of the traditional parties.
One part of the problem is that the traditional parties have failed to recognize the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the growing geographical inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that truly matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are all alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
The social sciences could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from its path.
The chasm between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of the governments has widened into a abyss.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing income and other indicator gaps between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron implemented it, no national head of government had introduced tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the pollsters became the basis for Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct against women, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of his opponents' jokes; however, the laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, in which activists distribute flyers at intervals and encourage the candidates.
That was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace composed of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this perspective, the sole purpose of a party is to gain and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and launch petitions.
But this model no longer works.
The citizens nowadays refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation emerged.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own agency and not as pawns in the game of others.
In addition, the governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn over the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The currently most pressing political challenges – climate change, religious extremism, digital transformations, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions solely from national governments.
These challenges demand profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at the sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the entry barriers for political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and entrenched support networks.
Who can effectively navigate Google, Twitter, and Facebook does not need a centuries-old party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not only on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems in order to strengthen the communities in this way.
Such projects should today be considered indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding paths for political and civic engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policies "live" every day, the parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Reconnecting with the concerns of voters goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics at the local level.
